commitResults.messageBody:
Previously, when calling the default constructor of the Car class, a Car object will be instantiated if both the model name and license plate number are string type values, and the price is a double type value. This means that even negative values, as long as they are of double type, will still be considered as valid and stored as the price attribute of the Car object.

However, in our context of price, negative price doesn't make sense. Hence, the price value entered by the user will first pass through a simple conditional check, and an exception will be thrown if the price is negative.

commitResults.messageBody:
License plate number format is standardised. To simplify things, ALL license plate number must follow the format: "SXX####X", in order to be deemed valid.

Valid license plate number requirements:
- MUST start with "S"
- "X" represents any letter from [A - Z]
- "#" represents any number from [0 - 9]

Add new method to format car price to 2dp
commitResults.messageBody:
Whenever money is concerned and there is a decimal point, the result should always be formatted to 2 d.p. However, when storing the result as a double, the program always removes the trailing zeroes.

For example, when assigning a value of "16.10" to a double type variable "result", the program will store it as "16.1". Therefore, this new method ensures that when the car list is printed out, the price will be formatted to 2dp for ALL cars. (i.e. 16.10 instead of 16.1). In addition, for whole number/integers, only the int value will be printed out. (i.e. 16 if the value stored is "16" or "16.00", etc.)

The updated method improves the flexibility of the license plate number requirement. Previously, the requirement was that the numeric part of the license plate number MUST BE a 4 digit number. Technically, since it has to be a 4 digit number, the accepted range is only from 1000 to 9999. However, in order to bypass this and input a number less than 1000, users can input leading zeroes at the front of the number (e.g. 0055), and this is undesirable.

Based on the real world, the accpetable range of numbers is from 1 to 9999. Therefore, in an attempt to model after the real world and be as realistic as possible, this new updated method allows users to do just that. The updated method now accepts numbers ranging from 1 to 9999, without any leading zeroes.

commitResults.messageBody: Previously, only price with a decimal point will be formatted to 2 d.p. In the event that the specified price is an integer/whole number, the formatted price will still remain as an integer/whole number. In the updated method, ALL prices will now be formatted to 2 d.p, regardless whether there is a decimal point. For example, even if the specified price is 16, the method will return a formatted price of 16.00.
